WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:23.600
Ben, welcome to POSIT Conference, thanks so much for coming, it's great to see you

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:24.600
as always.

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:25.600
Great to see you.

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:31.200
You came in for the summit on Sunday, you and some colleagues, awesome, well I'm so

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:36.080
glad we got a chance to connect and I really want to highlight the awesome work that you're

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:40.439
doing, your team's working on, and just let the community know about the things you're

00:00:40.439 --> 00:00:41.439
doing.

00:00:41.439 --> 00:00:45.759
But I think like, before we jump into that, I'd love to take a few steps back into like

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:53.599
how it all started, like how did you get into pharma, what did you do to Bridget and of

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:55.840
all things like Shiny too?

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:57.240
Yeah, yeah, for sure.

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:00.840
So how I got into pharma, it's a weird story.

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:05.959
So I'd been a data scientist for a long time, I'd worked in consulting and different things

00:01:05.959 --> 00:01:11.400
like that, and had lived that consulting lifestyle, you know, fly out Monday morning to some place

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:13.639
and then fly home kind of Thursday night.

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:17.680
So I think you and I have similar backgrounds with IBM and everything.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.959
And one day GSK, they reached out and they said, look, we're trying to build a data science

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:28.879
capability, we'll teach you pharma, you teach us data science, and you'll be part of what's

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:33.239
called the ESPRIT program, which is like this executive leadership training.

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:38.519
And you do some rotations, and we'll find you a job eventually in the organization.

00:01:38.519 --> 00:01:42.360
So that was kind of my entrance into pharma.

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:47.080
Like what really appealed to me, why I wanted to work in pharma was, I had a lot of great

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:52.800
tools and toolkits with data science, open source, cloud platforms, things like that.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.639
But I hadn't found kind of like that passion area, that passion industry.

00:01:56.639 --> 00:02:00.760
And a lot of my family, so like my mom, her brothers and sisters, her parents, they've

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:01.760
all had cancer.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:04.720
At some point, I'm going to have cancer probably.

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:09.559
So being able to work in an industry to actually show impact, I don't need to know the science,

00:02:09.559 --> 00:02:13.960
but I can, you know, work on the pipeline or help people move assets through our pipeline

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:18.039
to, you know, actually have impact on those patients, really hit close to home.

00:02:18.039 --> 00:02:21.800
And that's kind of really what appealed to me and why I wanted to join the pharma org.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:26.080
It's such an awesome story of bringing data science into pharma.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:29.639
And the work that you were doing before was GIS.

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:33.880
GIS, cybersecurity, yeah, just trying to solve problems.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:39.199
And it's amazing to see the influence that you're having in the community and at GSK

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:43.000
on work like agile and better practices around software development.

00:02:43.039 --> 00:02:45.880
Did you bring that with you into that role from?

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:50.360
Yeah, so when they initially hired me, the idea was for me to really focus on helping

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:55.000
them think through like how to build our SCE, our scientific compute environment, so cloud

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:56.720
architecture and things like that.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:01.199
And kind of the way it played out, it was, there's actually a big niche for like, how

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:03.279
do people actually think about user design?

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:09.039
How do you think about actually coming up with values within development teams to interact

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:10.039
with users?

00:03:10.039 --> 00:03:13.559
How do you think about, okay, we built something, but just because you build something doesn't

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:14.919
mean it's going to be adopted.

00:03:14.919 --> 00:03:18.759
So how do you actually think about putting in those support structures, but also at the

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:23.259
same time using those support structures as feedback to improve our data products?

00:03:23.259 --> 00:03:24.839
So that was kind of the niche I found.

00:03:24.839 --> 00:03:29.639
So eventually just kind of building out tools, you know, obviously we still, or I spent a

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:34.639
lot of time working, coding up things, working with different people, but at the same time,

00:03:34.639 --> 00:03:39.479
really leaning on support structures in order to understand sort of what do users need?

00:03:39.479 --> 00:03:42.919
Because at the end of the day, with this big transition that we're making, we have

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:48.000
to make our user feel as least amount of friction as possible in order to be able to kind of

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.080
adopt our different open source tools.

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:51.080
Yeah.

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:53.240
And you work with such a rockstar team.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:59.000
I mean, Christina Fillmore and Andy Nichols and Ellis and Becca.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.759
What is that like to have such an amazing crew around you?

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:03.759
I'm lucky.

00:04:04.679 --> 00:04:10.320
I mean, they make the job easy because I think what is really crucial is it's not only the

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:16.440
individuals to be able to go out and talk to people, but it's like who can actually

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:19.480
take that user feedback and then turn it into a reality.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:25.679
And I think being able to pair teams together, not only like a very solid engineering team,

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:31.480
but also a very solid kind of user feedback support, you know, someone to, you know, consulting

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:33.480
or voice of the customer, if you will.

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:38.760
Being able to merge those two together is what allows us to really make those very solid

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:40.799
data products with such a small team.

00:04:40.799 --> 00:04:44.359
Because at the end of the day, we are not big, but we're small and agile.

00:04:44.359 --> 00:04:51.320
I think it's such an amazing thing that you have this awesome team and you have thought

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:55.959
right off the bat, how do we help support the community within the organization?

00:04:55.959 --> 00:04:56.959
Yeah.

00:04:56.959 --> 00:04:57.959
Right.

00:04:57.959 --> 00:05:03.640
Can you talk a little bit about what was the spark for the Accelerate R team and how

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:04.640
that came about?

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:05.640
Yeah, sure.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:08.720
So Accelerate R is one of my, I guess, things I'm most proud about.

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:10.279
I've talked about it here at Posit.

00:05:10.279 --> 00:05:12.239
I've talked about it in some of the other conferences.

00:05:12.239 --> 00:05:17.359
But I think the thing that we saw and realized is we were doing tons of workshops, tons of

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:22.079
classes on R. And then all of a sudden, no one was using it.

00:05:22.079 --> 00:05:25.320
And we were trying to figure out for a long time, why is no one using R?

00:05:25.799 --> 00:05:32.399
What we realized is a user or an individual within our Biostats organization, they would

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:37.559
take a training, they would do a workshop, but they actually wouldn't be able to get

00:05:37.559 --> 00:05:43.239
the ability to use our open source tools until 12, 18 months later on in their study.

00:05:43.239 --> 00:05:46.760
And I can't remember why I had breakfast.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:52.079
No one's going to remember what do I do with Tidyverse or anything 18 months down the road.

00:05:52.079 --> 00:05:58.839
And so the spark was really thinking about not training in the sense of how do we train

00:05:58.839 --> 00:06:01.959
people but thinking about training and then learning.

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:06.679
And I think that's a really important concept because I think training is really easy.

00:06:06.679 --> 00:06:11.160
You find some documents, you create the documents, you create whatever it is, and people can

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:12.160
go and do it.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:14.000
But how does someone learn?

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.040
How does someone learn while trying to deliver against deadlines?

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:24.320
And that is a really important question to think about because we're not university students.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:26.140
We're not college students.

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:31.480
We don't have the ability to spend a semester to learn something and then go apply it.

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:33.239
We have to learn on the fly.

00:06:33.239 --> 00:06:36.440
And starting to think about our user in that different way about how does someone actually

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:39.600
learn within an organization is really crucial.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.920
And so that's why we started Accelerate R. We go and sit with a clinical study team.

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:47.720
It's a very intense eight to ten weeks where we're literally training them and then we're

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:53.480
using those eight to ten weeks to learn about what's wrong in our workflow to then build

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.480
a tool during those eight to ten weeks.

00:06:55.480 --> 00:07:01.079
So it's not only us supporting people, teaching, having them learn, and then upskilling those

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:06.040
capabilities as we make our transition, but it's also giving us the feedback that we need

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:10.200
to figure out what are the actual tools instead of us making guesses.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:14.519
And I think that balance is really what's leading to a lot of success for us.

00:07:14.519 --> 00:07:19.720
And I think it's such an impactful way to get feedback from your users because it's

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:24.799
created and the output of that has brought forth some really important packages like

00:07:24.799 --> 00:07:31.279
T4mat and Slushy where you identified challenges and issues that your user base had and instead

00:07:31.279 --> 00:07:36.160
of trying to find a workaround or something from the community, you said, hey, let's build

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:37.959
this and solve it for them.

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:38.959
Exactly.

00:07:38.959 --> 00:07:43.359
And I think the thing that is great is because of sort of our time box engagements, we have

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:44.440
to get something out.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:47.799
So like Slushy, I think Becca was like, all right, let's do this.

00:07:47.799 --> 00:07:52.640
And she built it maybe in like a month because since we have that time box thing, we don't

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:56.640
have long periods of time where we can go away and we can think about it and we have

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:58.959
to deliver it and we have to see the impact.

00:07:58.959 --> 00:08:03.200
And being able to see the impact quickly and then continuously get that feedback again

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:07.239
is another input for how we make really strong data products.

00:08:07.239 --> 00:08:11.399
And I think it's something that speaks so much to me because groups will reach out to

00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:15.880
me to do a workshop and I always tell them, look, I'm happy to do a workshop for you.

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:22.119
And I hope that it sparks further learnings, but really what's needed in-house is a competency

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:28.959
center or some type of group that manages the change that's happening in the drug development

00:08:28.959 --> 00:08:29.959
space.

00:08:29.959 --> 00:08:30.959
Absolutely.

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:31.959
And your team just tackled that.

00:08:31.959 --> 00:08:37.080
And I joke all the time that last year your talk was about the downside of workshops,

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:39.919
which is so funny because I do so many workshops, right?

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:48.320
But I do always preach the side of it needs to be part of a center that your group manages

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:53.000
that you think about how do we take people from the commercial software into the open

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.000
source side.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Exactly.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:01.520
And that's the other thing that we love about it is we try to eat our own dog food.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:06.919
So as soon as we kind of finish an iteration, we try to get some of those individuals to

00:09:06.919 --> 00:09:08.640
start contributing to the open source.

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:14.559
So like, for example, the team that we did slushy with was an oncology team, and then

00:09:14.559 --> 00:09:19.239
they started to directly contribute to Admiral Onco based off sort of some of those lessons

00:09:19.239 --> 00:09:23.619
and some of those learnings that we had as an Accelerate R iteration.

00:09:23.619 --> 00:09:28.880
So like being able to not only train, not only upskill, but also figure out a way for

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:33.359
individuals or inspire individuals to start contributing to the open source.

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:38.880
It just makes everything a lot more solid, if you will, based off that.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.320
And talking about contributing to open source, you contribute to open source, right?

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:46.440
I've seen you have a package with Christina for Bayesian analysis.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:47.440
What's that like?

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:48.440
Complicated.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:55.719
So, yeah, we're, we really, so it's our first stats package, which I think is pretty special

00:09:55.719 --> 00:09:59.039
for us within GSK.

00:09:59.039 --> 00:10:03.080
It's focused on Bayesian dynamic borrowing for robust mixtures priors.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:05.400
Good luck saying that ten times fast.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:10.760
But it's really focused on some of our cutting edge stats methodology, which we partner with

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:17.799
some of the other individuals on our team and basically try to take out of their brain

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:20.840
and translate it into something that, you know, the community can use.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:24.880
And that, you know, it's always super exciting to be able to be part of that.

00:10:25.039 --> 00:10:26.039
Plus, it has a great name.

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:27.039
Yeah.

00:10:27.039 --> 00:10:28.039
Beast.

00:10:28.039 --> 00:10:29.039
Yeah.

00:10:29.039 --> 00:10:31.080
We're thinking maybe a gritty logo or something as our hex icon.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:36.280
So I feel like one of the things that you often hear in the open source community is

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:41.640
that good software development and engineering is a critical part of statistical computing.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:42.640
Sure.

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:49.640
There's a group, OpenStatsWare, that you're part of, that really is about this.

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:51.359
What motivated you to get involved?

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:52.840
Yeah.

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:59.640
I mean, I think what really motivated me to get involved was seeing that there's a gap.

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:05.320
So you have a lot of our PhD level statisticians that come into the organization and their

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:08.559
intelligence is just something I can't comprehend.

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:14.239
But watching them fumble around with GitHub, as everyone does when you first start it,

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:16.119
was kind of eye opening.

00:11:16.119 --> 00:11:20.679
And a lot of also statisticians, they live in the base R world and they don't have a

00:11:20.679 --> 00:11:25.599
ton of exposure to tidyverse or packages and things like that, and how it can improve

00:11:25.599 --> 00:11:26.859
their workflows.

00:11:26.859 --> 00:11:33.400
So being involved with that group and some other groups internally at GSK to upskill

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:38.679
our statisticians to think about, how do I actually do version control?

00:11:38.679 --> 00:11:40.559
How do I use it to my benefit?

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:45.799
How do I use it in order to be able to track things and share it so I'm not just passing

00:11:45.799 --> 00:11:47.679
code around in the organization?

00:11:47.679 --> 00:11:53.039
That has been really crucial for us being able to upskill and it's a partnership.

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:57.520
They teach us stats or more sets, but we teach them some of the other tools that make their

00:11:57.520 --> 00:11:58.520
lives easier.

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:00.159
And at the end of the day, that's the goal.

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:04.599
We all want to try to do things well and being able to have kind of more tools in our tool

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:07.679
belt in order to accomplish that is how we do it.

00:12:07.679 --> 00:12:12.479
So we've talked about going from commercial software into open source and learning new

00:12:12.479 --> 00:12:14.039
tools like Git.

00:12:14.039 --> 00:12:17.799
It seems like a critical component of this for most of the organizations that I work

00:12:17.799 --> 00:12:20.000
with are tables.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:21.000
Yeah.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:22.919
GSK has thought a lot about tables.

00:12:22.919 --> 00:12:23.919
We have.

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:24.919
Yeah.

00:12:24.919 --> 00:12:25.919
Yeah.

00:12:25.919 --> 00:12:31.359
So obviously we have our table solution called TFORMAT, which Christina wrote, but also supported

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:33.840
by Becca Krause and Ellis Hughes.

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.520
And then Becca is the current owner and maintainer of that.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:42.960
And we like to think about how to leverage TFORMAT obviously in our workflows, but also

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:47.559
how do we leverage services around TFORMAT to help others?

00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:51.919
So obviously if you're a hardcore R user, you know how to use R. Great.

00:12:51.919 --> 00:12:54.919
Go to the TFORMAT package and things like that.

00:12:54.919 --> 00:12:59.039
But what if you're not an R user, say you're a medical writer or say you're a scientist

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:00.039
or something like that?

00:13:00.039 --> 00:13:02.719
How do I interact with TFORMAT?

00:13:02.719 --> 00:13:07.000
And Becca just gave a talk about it, but we have an open source tool called TFORMAT Builder,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.119
which is essentially a shiny app GUI that allows you to kind of go through and step

00:13:12.119 --> 00:13:16.239
by step be able to initialize and create a TFORMAT table.

00:13:16.239 --> 00:13:18.880
So it helps guide you along the way.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:23.080
And I think one of the great things about TFORMAT, TFORMAT Builder is it gives an entry

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:27.400
point for someone that's R curious or open source curious, but doesn't know where to

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:29.359
start and it kind of guides them.

00:13:29.359 --> 00:13:33.979
So I think that is being able to have that entry point that's not so overwhelming for

00:13:33.979 --> 00:13:39.200
someone that wants to dabble is really crucial for how you kind of build your community.

00:13:39.320 --> 00:13:45.400
I feel like you've done so many awesome things in the group that's managing these new users

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:48.280
or existing users that are hitting roadblocks.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:52.659
Are there new things on the horizon that you have thought about incorporating?

00:13:52.659 --> 00:13:55.400
You hear a lot of times the buzz of Gen AI.

00:13:55.400 --> 00:13:57.119
Has that come up for you?

00:13:57.119 --> 00:13:58.919
We've been thinking about it, sure.

00:13:58.919 --> 00:14:03.840
But I think for us, where we want to focus potentially is how we apply it.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:06.900
And I don't know if we're the right people, honestly.

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:08.119
It's so new.

00:14:08.119 --> 00:14:12.119
I think there's a lot of smart people out there that's going to figure it out.

00:14:12.119 --> 00:14:17.119
But I think at the end of the day, what we like to focus on is how do we have impact now?

00:14:17.119 --> 00:14:24.479
So I think, as I mentioned, one of the things is around R adoption and sort of where is

00:14:24.479 --> 00:14:25.479
the industry going?

00:14:25.479 --> 00:14:32.200
So one of the things that we were talking about in the summit on Sunday is how do you

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:34.760
know how much R adoption is going on?

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:36.719
How many studies are actually using R?

00:14:36.719 --> 00:14:41.719
So within GSK, we've piloted some ideas using version control, which we have a new policy

00:14:41.719 --> 00:14:47.039
that everyone needs to put all their code in GitHub within Biostats.

00:14:47.039 --> 00:14:53.440
So it allows us to be able to answer the question of at a study level, how much R is being used?

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:57.760
And being able to use sort of that kind of information allows us to be better with how

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:00.039
we target things and how we support things.

00:15:00.039 --> 00:15:04.520
And to me, that's kind of like a new frontier, because then we can really start to kind of

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:05.780
pick up acceleration.

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:09.340
I think Gen AI is definitely interesting.

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.340
We have the problem of reproducibility.

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:17.580
How do you answer the question of if I've created some code with a Gen AI product, it's

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:18.580
a black box.

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:22.580
And some of our consumers, our regulators, might not like that.

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:28.179
So I think there's still a lot to think about that we'll figure out over a few years.

00:15:28.179 --> 00:15:29.940
But it's coming down.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:30.940
We know it's coming.

00:15:30.940 --> 00:15:35.140
I heard you mention that critical word of reproducibility, and it's such an important

00:15:35.140 --> 00:15:41.340
part of what GSK does, is the metadata-driven analysis and touching back to packages like

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:43.580
MetaCore and tools like that.

00:15:43.580 --> 00:15:44.580
Yeah.

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:48.659
It's another set of tools that we thought were really important, our open-source part

00:15:48.659 --> 00:15:50.659
of the Farmiverse, things like that.

00:15:50.659 --> 00:15:54.140
But yeah, we have a ton of things around metadata.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:58.820
And then there's a new paradigm coming out around ARDs, Analysis Results Datasets.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:00.280
And we're all going to it.

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:04.059
I think everyone is waiting for the CDES standard to come out.

00:16:04.059 --> 00:16:08.820
That way we can then all apply our own standard on the set of standards.

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:14.260
But I think what's exciting about that is we're able to have an end-to-end pipeline

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:17.260
using R. And I don't think that was true two years ago.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.859
So now we can say, from metadata to table, we can do it.

00:16:21.859 --> 00:16:24.559
Metadata to figure, but ggplot at the end, we can do it.

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:28.580
And I think that's what's really exciting, especially for us this year, is being able

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:37.659
to say, as soon as your metadata hits within your clinical trial database, you can start

00:16:37.659 --> 00:16:38.659
your pipeline.

00:16:38.659 --> 00:16:39.659
And that's really exciting.

00:16:39.659 --> 00:16:47.059
And I feel like GSK and T4MAT was very early to that ARD, ARS format from CDES.

00:16:47.059 --> 00:16:51.140
And you're seeing tools now like GT Summary that's incorporating that as well.

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:55.219
So it's going to be interesting to see where that takes off.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:01.219
I feel like there's another component to the drug development space that's creeping in

00:17:01.219 --> 00:17:02.859
that's quite popular is Python.

00:17:02.859 --> 00:17:09.380
Has your team thought about how to approach that within the Accelerate R team?

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:10.660
We've thought about it.

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:16.459
But the current way of thinking, essentially, is we think Python is great, but for those

00:17:16.459 --> 00:17:19.219
kind of underlying data engineering tasks.

00:17:19.219 --> 00:17:22.900
At the end of the day, R is a statistical compute software.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:24.699
And we need to do stats.

00:17:24.699 --> 00:17:32.500
So right now, I think there's going to be, as we start moving into different environments,

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:39.099
whether it be cloud environments and data being stored in cloud in Parquet format or

00:17:39.099 --> 00:17:43.540
XYZ, I think we will start touching some of those other languages.

00:17:43.540 --> 00:17:50.900
But I think they'll be how we serve it up to our statistical programmers or statisticians

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:55.939
who fundamentally want to use R because of the stats power behind it.

00:17:55.939 --> 00:17:57.660
So we will.

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.020
I just don't know how much.

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:03.459
Not everyone's going to be touching it, but there is a future.

00:18:03.459 --> 00:18:06.459
So you've been here for the summit, the workshops, the conference.

00:18:06.459 --> 00:18:08.619
You're going to go back, hopefully relax.

00:18:08.619 --> 00:18:09.619
What are you going to do?

00:18:09.619 --> 00:18:13.579
I'm sure answer a bunch of emails.

00:18:13.579 --> 00:18:18.359
I'm really excited about a lot of the things around some of the R pharma topics.

00:18:18.359 --> 00:18:23.119
To me, there was a topic around how do you go SaaS programmer to R that obviously speaks

00:18:23.119 --> 00:18:25.479
very close to my heart.

00:18:25.479 --> 00:18:29.520
But there was a lot of things also thinking about how can we use some of the products

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:33.359
you all have put out, like use this for package development.

00:18:33.359 --> 00:18:40.359
How can we take that and maybe put a wrapper on top to make GitHub easier for a statistician

00:18:40.359 --> 00:18:44.599
who might not have that background in computer science or how version control works, but

00:18:44.599 --> 00:18:45.959
they need to use it.

00:18:45.959 --> 00:18:53.319
And so to me, what's exciting is being able to take what's out there, put our spin on

00:18:53.319 --> 00:18:56.119
it and then put it out for others to use.

00:18:56.119 --> 00:19:02.160
Maybe when we put something out, either another large pharma can take it and use it or a small

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:03.160
pharma.

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:08.319
And I think that's where I'm kind of curious about where we go is what happens to those

00:19:08.319 --> 00:19:14.040
medium and small pharmas in this big transition and how do we help them along in the process.

00:19:14.119 --> 00:19:20.040
It's a pretty amazing thing and you see this quite often in the ecosystem where tools like

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:27.280
Admiral were built off of dplyr and GT Summary is built off of GT and you have T4mat that

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:28.880
extends GT.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:32.920
And it's, I think, a really cool way to take that foundational package and start to build

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:36.160
the things that we need for the organization that we have.

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:37.160
Yeah, for sure.

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:41.880
And I think the other thing that's great about it is since we're all leveraging these open

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:46.800
source tools and putting them all out, it allows us to kind of standardize and it allows

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:49.640
us to really focus on the things that matter.

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:53.599
Like at the end of the day for pharma, what we want to focus on is the science.

00:19:53.599 --> 00:19:57.380
We don't really want to focus on like, we don't have the same competitive advantage,

00:19:57.380 --> 00:20:02.140
we don't get a competitive advantage between like who has a better tabling package or anything.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:05.880
It's something that we like to do because we like to think about how users interact

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:06.880
with data.

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:11.219
But at the end of the day, we like to focus on science and if this allows people to focus

00:20:11.219 --> 00:20:13.780
more on the science, then it's a big win.

00:20:13.780 --> 00:20:18.140
You know, it's a topic that's come up so much with my interactions with the pharma is how

00:20:18.140 --> 00:20:19.380
do we standardize things?

00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:25.199
And it seems like one of the lowest hanging fruit in that space is around TLGs and standardizing

00:20:25.199 --> 00:20:28.339
on the standard reports that they make.

00:20:28.339 --> 00:20:32.500
There's a new initiative, which was originally called Falcon, has now moved into Cardinal,

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:33.500
I believe.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:35.300
Have you seen that or part of it?

00:20:35.300 --> 00:20:36.300
A little bit.

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:39.660
I've seen sort of where, I've seen where it's going.

00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:42.260
I think if it works for your organization, use it.

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:47.819
I think the beauty of some of our open source communities like ASA, OpenStats, or Pharmiverse

00:20:47.819 --> 00:20:52.339
is there's a real strong push for everyone to contribute and then you figure out what

00:20:52.339 --> 00:20:53.780
works for your organization.

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:58.219
And I think that's kind of the beauty of sort of these package ecosystems.

00:20:58.219 --> 00:21:03.939
Your ability to take something that is fully kind of modular and figure out how to plug

00:21:03.939 --> 00:21:07.660
it into your workflow is what's great about it.

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:13.859
And so to me, I think if Falcon or some of these very, not rigid, but some of these ideas

00:21:13.859 --> 00:21:18.260
on how it is that we standardize, if that works for you and your company, great.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:21.459
If it doesn't work for you and you want to use something else that's available out there

00:21:21.459 --> 00:21:24.140
that someone is maintaining, great.

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:26.939
And it really depends on what it is that works best for you.

00:21:26.939 --> 00:21:31.780
I think it's a great story because pharmas are all so different in the way that they

00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:32.780
process things.

00:21:32.780 --> 00:21:36.900
And it's basically saying, here's an ecosystem of packages that you can pick off of that

00:21:36.900 --> 00:21:39.140
are reflective of the processes that you have.

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:40.140
Exactly.

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:46.219
You know, one thing I've always thought with GSK is that, you know, Andy Nichols being

00:21:46.219 --> 00:21:50.900
critical on the R Validation Hub and the R Validation Hub white paper being such a critical

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:56.859
piece of pharma on the open source side, you know, I'm sure that must have helped get things

00:21:56.859 --> 00:21:59.140
underway for GSK.

00:21:59.140 --> 00:22:00.140
For sure.

00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:06.180
I think being able to clearly define what do we mean by validation is the most crucial

00:22:06.180 --> 00:22:07.180
thing.

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:11.939
I mentioned it in my talk a little bit earlier, but one of the things that I remember early

00:22:11.939 --> 00:22:16.260
back before everything was validated is like, what does code execution mean?

00:22:16.260 --> 00:22:17.979
Does it mean a .exe file?

00:22:17.979 --> 00:22:22.280
Like is it literally an execution file or does it just mean you can run the code interactively?

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:27.579
And I think being able to figure out and define these are the things we care about, reproducibility,

00:22:27.579 --> 00:22:31.859
the ability to trace, or traceability, the ability to say, yes, we trust this.

00:22:31.859 --> 00:22:35.579
We trust the outputs and we trust the outputs that are going to come from these tools that

00:22:35.579 --> 00:22:37.859
we're using is really crucial.

00:22:37.859 --> 00:22:41.260
And being able to take that framework and then apply it internally.

00:22:41.260 --> 00:22:44.380
So we apply it in a certain way at GSK.

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:50.060
Another company can take those ideas and apply it for their QA department, but being able

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:54.380
to say, yes, these are the things that we care about, I think is a big step forward

00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:59.140
for us to be really feel comfortable for how it is that we deliver and how do we trust

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:00.140
what we create.

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:01.140
Yeah.

00:23:01.140 --> 00:23:04.780
Well, I have absolutely enjoyed chatting with you.

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:06.660
You've got a lot of the conference left.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:10.819
Any talks you're looking forward to attending?

00:23:10.819 --> 00:23:15.739
The thing I love coming here is being able to see not only what are other pharmas doing,

00:23:15.739 --> 00:23:17.560
but what is everyone else doing?

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:23.699
And I think one of the things that I learned coming into GSK is we can learn a ton from

00:23:23.699 --> 00:23:24.859
financial services.

00:23:24.859 --> 00:23:30.500
We can learn a ton from United States Geological Survey.

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:34.819
Being able to take sort of like lessons learned for people's individual organizations and

00:23:34.819 --> 00:23:39.380
then think about what it is that they did and kind of put our own twist is always a

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:42.619
great way for us to keep innovating and pushing things forward.

00:23:42.619 --> 00:23:47.479
If we just kind of stay within our internal pharma land, we're all going to kind of say

00:23:47.479 --> 00:23:48.479
a lot of similar things.

00:23:48.479 --> 00:23:52.739
But being able to see that kind of that cross-industry problem solving is really crucial for how

00:23:52.739 --> 00:23:55.140
it is that we continue to innovate.

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:56.819
I think it's fantastic.

00:23:56.819 --> 00:24:00.979
You get to mix with different people, diverse groups, and different industries here.

00:24:00.979 --> 00:24:03.780
And hopefully you take a lot back to your team.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:04.780
Hopefully.

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:05.780
Yeah.

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:06.780
Well, thank you so much.

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:10.140
I've had a great time and enjoyed the rest of the conference.

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:13.099
And hopefully we'll connect.

00:24:13.099 --> 00:24:15.560
Any other conferences coming up this year you're going to go to?

00:24:15.560 --> 00:24:19.380
My hope is to get into the rPharma conference.

00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:24.420
But rPharma, unfortunately, I won't be at Fuse EU, but I'll be at potentially Fuse.

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:27.060
And then, you know, wherever things pop up.

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:28.060
And Orlando.

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:29.060
Oh, of course.

00:24:29.060 --> 00:24:30.060
Yeah.

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:33.060
Orlando in March after a Northeast winter, I'm ready to go there.

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:34.060
Sign me up.

00:24:34.060 --> 00:24:35.060
Exactly.

00:24:35.060 --> 00:24:36.060
Exactly.

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:37.060
All right.

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:38.060
Thank you, Ben.

00:24:38.060 --> 00:24:38.060


